{
  "focus": "conclusion-readiness",
  "target_id": "q_001",
  "target_type": "question",
  "verdict": "address_first",
  "strengths": [
    "Independence analysis for the bride's given name 'Elizabeth' is genuinely sound (Standard 46). src_001 (marriage index, collection 1473015, informant = bride self) and src_002 (Bitton baptism, collection 1718965, informant = household member) are different record types, different collections, different informant units, and different registers. Two real independent sources — not a shared-informant illusion. This is exactly the kind of unit-counting the standard asks for.",
    "Informant analysis on a_005 and a_006 is disciplined. Both are correctly held at information_quality 'indeterminate' with named informant_proximity 'household_member' and honest informant_bias_notes acknowledging the specific informant is unstated. You resisted the temptation to inflate a baptism register to 'primary' for the mother's name. Good calibration.",
    "The Mary/Elizabeth discrepancy (log_009 vs log_011) was resolved with real reasoning, not a rubber stamp: you anchored 'Elizabeth' in the earlier 1830 entry from the same register series and assessed the 1832 'Mary' as an indexer error. The logic is correct.",
    "Negative and blocked results are documented with rigor (Standard 13): log_003 (Nonconformist nil), log_008/log_010 (Bristol-collection nil), log_005 (403 on original image), log_006/log_007 (subscription-blocked, URLs generated). The audit trail distinguishes searched-nil from unsearched. This is craftsmanship.",
    "You followed through on prior mentor findings: the FAN Bitton baptism search flagged in ev_001 was executed (pli_003, log_004/log_009/log_011), and the in-progress plan items flagged in ev_003 were resolved to 'skipped' with documented barriers. Good follow-through.",
    "Geographic plausibility holds: Bitton is roughly 6 miles east of Bristol, and src_001's note correctly records Bristol as a county of itself within historic Gloucestershire in 1828. The marriage-at-Bristol / first-baptism-at-Bitton pattern is entirely normal and needs no flag."
  ],
  "must_address": [
    {
      "standard": "Standard 44 — identity / assembled research results",
      "issue": "The bride — the central subject of q_001 — resolves to a person whose id is literally 'PID-TODO', both in project.subject_person_ids and as the actual person id in tree.gedcomx.json, and as the target of pe_002, pe_004, pe_006, pe_008. Prior review ev_004 downgraded this to a 'cosmetic' non-blocking note. At the conclusion-readiness gate I disagree. A proof about this woman's maiden name whose central figure resolves to a placeholder identifier is not traceable: a reader cannot follow the conclusion to a real, stable tree person. This is tolerable during research; it is not tolerable in a proof about identity.",
      "what_would_change_my_mind": "Replace 'PID-TODO' with the real, persistent person id for Elizabeth in the tree, and update project.subject_person_ids and the four pe_ links (pe_002, pe_004, pe_006, pe_008) to reference it. Once the subject resolves to a real identifier, this blocker closes.",
      "suggested_skill": "identity-resolution",
      "specific_action": "Assign the bride a real tree person id (not 'PID-TODO'), then update project.subject_person_ids and pe_002/pe_004/pe_006/pe_008 to point at it."
    },
    {
      "standard": "Standard 48 — conflict resolution / documented reasoning",
      "issue": "The Mary-vs-Elizabeth discrepancy is real conflicting evidence (1830 baptism indexes mother as 'Elizabeth'; 1832 sibling baptism from the same series indexes her as 'Mary'). Your resolution reasoning is good, but it lives only in prose inside a_006's notes and the exhaustive-declaration justification. The conflicts[] array is empty. A proof cannot cite a resolution that was never registered as a conflict with a four-part rationale (problem / evidence presented / which is more reliable and why / why the less-reliable version exists). Right now the proof would have to re-derive this on the fly.",
      "what_would_change_my_mind": "Register the discrepancy as a formal conflict object with a resolution_rationale that follows the four-part structure. Your existing prose already contains the substance — it just needs to be captured as a citable conflict record.",
      "suggested_skill": "conflict-resolution",
      "specific_action": "Add a conflict entry for the mother's-given-name discrepancy (a_006 'Elizabeth' vs the 1832 sibling 'Mary'), with a four-part resolution_rationale."
    },
    {
      "standard": "Standard 43 / Standards 64-67 — tier follows the evidence",
      "issue": "The evidence does not support a single uniform tier across all three elements of q_001, and the proof must not let the strong elements carry the weak one. Date (16 Nov 1828), place (Bristol), and given name (Elizabeth, independently corroborated across two collections) are strong. The maiden name 'Martin', however, rests on a single derivative index (src_001) with ZERO independent corroboration: the original image is 403-blocked (pli_007), the independent Ancestry index is subscription-blocked (pli_006), and the same_person test against the 1811 Elizabeth Martin christening was inconclusive (score ~0.000009, driven by data sparsity on the marriage persona, not by disproof). 'Martin' is Probable, not Proved. A conclusion that labels the whole finding 'Proved' would inflate the surname past what the evidence bears.",
      "what_would_change_my_mind": "Either (a) write the proof with an explicitly split conclusion — date/place/given-name at the higher tier, maiden name 'Martin' at Probable with the single-source limitation stated in the narrative itself; or (b) obtain one genuine independent corroboration of 'Martin' (the 403-blocked original image via an authenticated FamilySearch session or Gloucestershire Archives, or the Ancestry collection 5156 index). Either path makes the tier honest."
    }
  ],
  "consider_addressing": [
    {
      "standard": "Standard 38-39 — information-quality classification",
      "issue": "a_002 is classified information_quality 'primary' on the reasoning that the bride self-reported her surname at marriage. That is defensible in principle, but no one has examined the original register — the assumption that the bride (rather than the officiant or clerk) was the informant rests on an unseen record. The classification is fine to keep, but the proof narrative should acknowledge that the informant identity is inferred from record type, not observed.",
      "specific_action": "Add a one-line note to a_002 (or the proof narrative) that the 'self' informant proximity is inferred from the record type, pending examination of the original register."
    },
    {
      "standard": "Standard 32 — original vs derivative",
      "issue": "Every assertion rests on derivative indexes; no original has been examined. This is documented and does not block a proof, but the original image (ark:/61903/3:1:3QS7-996V-57FM) remains the single highest-value unopened door and is the most direct route to closing the 'Martin' limitation. Worth revisiting whenever authenticated access becomes available.",
      "specific_action": "Keep pli_007 open as a future-research item and cite it in the proof's 'further research' note."
    }
  ],
  "non_blocking_notes": [
    "validate_research_schema was not available in this environment, so mechanical schema compliance could not be machine-checked. Nothing in a manual read appeared malformed, but a schema pass is recommended before the proof is finalized.",
    "pl_002 status is 'active' while all its items are 'completed' or 'skipped' and the question is exhaustive_declared. Consider closing pl_002 to 'completed' for tidiness."
  ],
  "narrative_for_user": "# Mentor review: conclusion-readiness on q_001\n\n## What you've done well\n\nThis is genuinely careful work, and I want to name the specific things you got right before we talk about what's left.\n\n- **Your independence analysis for the given name 'Elizabeth' is the real thing (Standard 46).** src_001 is the marriage index with the bride as informant; src_002 is a Bitton baptism with a household member as informant — different collections, different record types, different registers, different informant units. That is two genuinely independent sources, not one source wearing two hats. This is exactly the unit-counting the standard asks for, and you did it correctly.\n- **Your informant calibration on the baptism (a_005, a_006) is disciplined.** You held both at 'indeterminate' and wrote honest bias notes acknowledging the informant isn't named. You resisted inflating a baptism register to 'primary' for the mother. That restraint is a mark of the craft.\n- **You resolved the Mary/Elizabeth discrepancy with actual reasoning** — anchoring 'Elizabeth' in the earlier 1830 entry and reading the 1832 'Mary' as an indexer error. The logic is sound.\n- **Your negative and blocked results are documented with rigor (Standard 13).** The nil Nonconformist search, the nil Bristol-collection searches, the 403 on the original image, the subscription-blocked external indexes — all logged, all distinguishing searched-nil from unsearched. That audit trail is what a peer reviewer wants to see.\n- **You followed through on prior findings.** The FAN Bitton search flagged in ev_001 was executed; the in-progress items flagged in ev_003 were resolved to documented 'skipped'. Good follow-through.\n\n## What to address before moving on\n\nThree things stand between this and a defensible proof.\n\n1. **Resolve the bride's identity (Standard 44).** The central figure of this question — Elizabeth herself — resolves to a person whose id is literally `PID-TODO`, in the project subject list, in the tree file, and across four person_evidence links. A previous review called this cosmetic. At the proof gate I have to disagree: a proof *about this woman's identity* cannot resolve her to a placeholder. A reader can't trace the conclusion to a real person. Assign her a real, persistent tree id and update the four pe_ links and the project subject list.\n\n2. **Register the Mary/Elizabeth discrepancy as a formal conflict (Standard 48).** Your resolution reasoning is good — but it only exists as prose in a note and in the exhaustive declaration. The `conflicts[]` array is empty. The proof needs a citable conflict object with the four-part rationale (problem / evidence / which is more reliable and why / why the weaker version exists). You already have the substance; it just needs to be captured as a record the proof can point to.\n\n3. **Tier the maiden name honestly (Standard 43).** This is the heart of it. Your date, place, and given name are strong — the given name is independently corroborated across two collections. But 'Martin' rests on a single derivative index with zero independent corroboration: the original image is 403-blocked, the Ancestry index is subscription-blocked, and the same_person test against the 1811 christening came back inconclusive (and that near-zero score is data sparsity, not disproof). 'Martin' is **Probable**, not Proved. Do not let the strength of the date and place carry the surname across the line. Write a split conclusion — the event facts at the higher tier, the maiden name at Probable with the single-source limitation stated in the narrative itself. That is not a weaker proof; it is an honest one, and honesty about limits is what makes a proof defensible.\n\nTo answer your three questions directly: (1) Yes — the evidence is sufficient to write a GPS-standard proof, provided the maiden-name limitation is stated rather than papered over. (2) The tier is split: event facts at the higher tier, 'Martin' at **Probable**. (3) Yes, there are integrity issues that would make the conclusion indefensible as-is — the placeholder identity and the unregistered conflict — but both are fixable without new field research.\n\n## Worth considering\n\n- a_002's 'primary / self' classification is defensible but rests on an unseen original — the assumption that the bride (not the clerk) was the informant is inferred from record type. Keep the classification, but say so in the narrative.\n- The original register image remains your highest-value unopened door (Standard 32). Keep it as a documented further-research item; it's the cleanest future path to promoting 'Martin' from Probable.\n\n## What would change my mind\n\n- **On identity:** give Elizabeth a real tree id and repoint subject_person_ids and pe_002/pe_004/pe_006/pe_008 — the blocker closes immediately.\n- **On the conflict:** capture the Mary/Elizabeth resolution as a formal conflict object with the four-part rationale.\n- **On tier:** either write the split conclusion with 'Martin' explicitly at Probable and the limitation stated in the narrative, OR obtain one genuine independent corroboration of 'Martin' (the 403-blocked original, or Ancestry collection 5156) — either path makes 'Proved' honest for the surname too."
}

